\date{2026-03-30}
\title{Segal types have #{\Delta^1}-discrete Homs}
\author{fredrikbakke}
\meta{external}{https://github.com/samtoth/agda-synthetic-categories/pull/86}
\tag{changelog}
\import{stt-macros}

\subtree{\title{Summary}
\p{
The standard argument for showing that [Segal types](stt-00AI) have
[#{\Delta^1}-discrete](stt-00B6) [Hom types](stt-00A9) goes via first demonstrating
the Hom family is [covariant](stt-00AY) (or contravariant), which does not seem to
hold without some additional axiom like [triangularity](stt-00CS). In this
contribution we instead formalise an alternative argument of this fact which does not
require any extra axioms, and instead takes advantage of the
[left and right homotopy characterisations](stt-00CI) of equality on morphisms.
}

\p{
For the proof, first observe that [it's enough to produce a map from morphisms to
equalities to deduce that a type is #{\Delta^1}-discrete](stt-00L4). We use this
construction on the Hom types themselves. Observe that any morphism of morphisms
#{\alpha : \Hom_{\Hom_A(a,b)}(f,g)} defines a degenerate square, i.e., a diagram
indexed by #{\Delta^1 \times \Delta^1} of the form

\quiver{
\begin{tikzcd}
  a && a \\
  \\
  b && b
\arrow[equals, from=1-1, to=1-3]
\arrow[equals, from=3-1, to=3-3]
\arrow[from=1-1, to=3-1, "f"']
\arrow[from=1-3, to=3-3, "g"]
\arrow[from=1-1, to=3-3, phantom, "\alpha"]
\end{tikzcd}
}

From squares we can extract a lower and an upper triangle even without simplicialty.
These triangles, since they are degenerate, are respectively
[left and right homotopies](stt-00CH) #{g \lhtpy \alpha|_\Delta} and
#{f \rhtpy \alpha|_\Delta}, where #{\alpha|_\Delta} is the diagonal
#{\alpha|_\Delta(i) \coloneqq \alpha(i,i)}, and in a Segal type those relations
characterise equality, so we can derive that #{f = g}. Thus, [the Hom types of a
Segal type are #{\Delta^1}-discrete](stt-00L5).
}
}
